    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The worst-case scenario is that you end up paying for their defense costs, even if they ultimately win the case, *and* you might have to pay the damages awarded against them. Because the clause is so broad, \"losses\" could encompass everything from legal fees and settlements to actual financial judgments. If a third party sues them, and that suit traces back to your design work, the client can point to that broad indemnification clause and demand you cover the entire bill.\n\nThis is why you need to know the scope of the risk—are they protecting against a small copyright claim, or are they trying to make you responsible for a massive product liability lawsuit stemming from your visual branding? If you are truly their shield against *everything*, you could be financially ruined by one unexpected design choice. It's a high-stakes gamble, and you need to negotiate for limitations.\n\nYou should absolutely try to limit this to specific, provable issues, like \"indemnification solely for claims arising from your direct breach of warranties regarding intellectual property.\" Anything beyond that is giving them too much power. Remember, if you sign that broad clause without limits, you are accepting the risk of every possible bad outcome, which is almost never worth it",
